== Prehistory ==
On [[Orkney]], Scotland, sea eagle bones have been found in 6,000-year-old burial mounds, among them the [[Tomb of the Eagles]], suggesting that the birds were revered by the prehistoric people there, a belief strengthened by the Pictish stone carvings of sea eagles from Orkney.{{sfn|The Nature of Scotland|p=49}} Cut marks have been found in white-tailed eagle talons in [[Krapina]], suggesting [[Neanderthal]]s' use of [[jewellery]].<ref name="Radovčić-2015">{{cite journal |last1=Radovčić |first1=D. |last2=Sršen |first2=A.O. |last3=Radovčić |first3=J. |last4=Frayer |first4=D.W. |year=2015 |title=Evidence for Neandertal Jewelry: Modified White-Tailed Eagle Claws at Krapina |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=10 |issue=3 e0119802 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0119802 |article-number=e0119802 |pmid=25760648 |pmc=4356571|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1019802R |doi-access=free}}</ref>

== Folklore ==
In [[Ireland]], in particular, sea eagles are associated with many beliefs. 

In Irish Celtic mythology, eagles generally symbolize the oldest and wisest of creatures, surpassed in age and wisdom only by the salmon.

In the Irish Gaelic language, the white-tailed eagle was poetically named Iolar súil na gréine — "the eagle with the sunlit eye" — referring to their sharp, piercing gaze and pale eyes. They were believed to possess such fierce, regal power that they could stare directly into the sun

In Irish culture, the sighting of a single eagle sitting on a crag was considered a foreboding omen of an approaching enemy, whereas seeing two eagles together was viewed as a symbol of peace.

The Measure of a Life: According to [[Kerry]] folklore, a sea eagle’s lifespan was said to encompass three crí — a measure of time so vast it represents digging a field, planting and harvesting potatoes, then planting oats, and leaving the field to lay fallow until no trace of cultivation remains. 

In the [[Shetland Isles]], Scotland, fishermen believed that as soon as a sea eagle appeared fish would rise to the surface, belly up; this led to some fishermen using eagle fat, smeared on their bait, to increase their catch.{{sfn|The Nature of Scotland|p=49}}

